==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*kwikwa-'', from Indo-European ''*gʷei-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[quik]], Old Saxon [[quik]] (Dutch [[kwik]]), Old High German [[kec]] (German [[keck]]), Old Norse [[kvikr]] (Swedish [[kvick]]), Gothic [[𐌵𐌹𐌿𐍃]].  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[vivus]], Baltic ''*gīwa-'' (Lithuanian [[gyvas|gývas]], Latvian [[dzivs]]), Slavic ''*zivo-'' (Old Church Slavonic [[живѫ]], Russian [[живой]]), Celtic ''*gwitu-'' (Old Irish [[biad]] ‘nourishment’, Irish [[biathaim]] ‘nourish’).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /kwɪk/

===Adjective===
'''cwic''
# [[living]], [[live]], [[alive]]
#:''Enoch cwic gewat mid cyning engla'': Enoch departed alive with the king of angels.
# mentally agile; [[intelligent]], [[keen]]

